Full Description: DART provides a variety of services for managing, treating and recycling industrial waste streams.  This process involves the treatment of off-site and on-site non-hazardous industrial wastewaters and/or landfill leachates typically containing heavy metals, oils and other organics. Wastewaters are processed in dedicated treatment tanks prior to final sewer discharge as authorized by permit from Water and Sewerage Departments. Wastewater treatment consists of one or more of the following processes: primary, secondary or tertiary treatment for metals precipitation, chemical oxidation, chemical reduction, coagulation, flocculation and carbon absorption. Solids generated from these processes are sent for further Sludge Treatment within the facility.

Description: P2 Inc.a vision to create new, innovative and useful products for the general aviation community.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Minneapolis-Saint Paul Area, Great Lakes, Midwestern US
Full Description: P2 Inc. was founded on a vision to create new, innovative and useful products for the general aviation community. Combining the knowledge gained from years of flying experience along with numerous talented engineering minds, P2 has developed a history of successful GA products. P2's first product, the 9600 Amphibian Gear Advisory System (AGAS), was developed in the early 90's. This device was the first one of its' kind to market and has dominated the field ever since. It is estimated that somewhere around 80% of the amphibian aircraft today have these units onboard and. The device has also been standard equipment on all new Wipline amphibious floats. With the 9600 program complete, work soon began on taking this technology to the retractable-gear general aviation aircraft, and the 6600 Audio Advisory System was born. In addition to monitoring landing gear, it sported several new features that are aimed at the high-performance retractable singles and light twins. The 6600 eventually evolved into the 6601 Audio Advisory System. This new version was developed as a result of the need to accommodate both pressurized and non-pressurized aircraft. The 6601 is currently STC-approved for installation in smallest retractable-gear aircraft, all the way up to the Raytheon King Air 90-series turboprop. Audio Advisory Systems are now installed in a wide variety of aircraft. In 2005, the Sky Buddy was brought to market. This portable device gave pilots a much needed low-cost heading and altitude reminder. TimeTrac, general aviation's first integrated flight record management system, received FAA approval in 2005. Over 700 different makes and models of aircraft are included in it's Approved Model List. Each one of P2's products are developed by a team that knows aviation. Committed to taking their products to a higher level of quality, reliability, safety and convenience, the company is teamed up with leaders in the avionics industry to assure that each product meets rigorous FAA/PMA standards.

Description: The idea that small or medium emergency services agencies had to do without good technology has always chaffed at us.
Headquarters Regions: Great Lakes, Midwestern US
Full Description: The idea that small or medium emergency services agencies had to do without good technology has always chaffed at us. We believe that ANY agency big or small should have access to the same data and tools. When we discovered that the Mutual Aid Box Alarm System had run on paper based box cards since it's inception the late 1960s we knew we had a golden opportunity to create a valuable and useful product. When MABAS is established as a mutual aid standard for an area the methods for dispatching, planning and emergency scene management changes. EMABAS by Mutual Aid Labs takes the manual paper driven process and makes it fully electronic that changes and updates when data and resources change and update. We've been writing our application for a year with the input of emergency services professionals from working MABAS divisions. Now we are ready to launch and change the face of MABAS forever.

Description: IotaBEAM provides IoT security solutions specifically designed to authenticate and secure low complexity IoT sensors and endpoint devices.
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, Silicon Valley, West Coast
Full Description: StarDust™ by IotaBEAM is an IoT security solution specifically designed to authenticate and secure low complexity IoT sensors and endpoint devices without a need for hardware or system redesign. Our encryption and authentication / communications scheme has been optimized for highly constrained devices: it takes a tiny footprint on the processor/memory and drain very minimum power from the battery.  Our communications protocol and sophisticated key management scheme are unique and difficult to decipher, with a single breach requiring significant time and compute effort.  Since each endpoint device has its own set of unpublished keys, a single breach will only affect one device and will not compromise the entire network.  Our solution will constantly monitor and detect any breach (or breach in progress) and can be instructed to shut down any device that has been compromised. Our security solution is designed to have low impact on the existing design: it encrypts data with the latest in non-hacked cryptography (which has been fully reviewed and analyzed by the crypto community) and authenticates devices with minimum message exchanged. The solution has been designed from the ground up to be easy to implement on any existing IoT platforms and processors without a need for any hardware or system redesign.  It is agnostic to any wireless access technologies (e.g. BLW, ZigBee, WiFi, LoRa, cellular IoT, etc.) and/or existing IP / cloud infrastructure. A demo of StarDust™ is available running on AWS. IotaBEAM was established in 2017 and is based in Palo Alto, California.
Industry Groups: Information Technology, Internet Services, Privacy and Security

Description: GLCF will manufacture carbon fiber in spooled format which will be provided to downstream companies for further processing such.

Full Description: GLCF will manufacture carbon fiber in spooled format which will be provided to downstream companies for further processing such as weaving, prepreging,compounding, etc. The initial product will be a "standard modulus"fiber which is in significant use in industrial applications ranging from Blades for Wind Turbines to Construction. Collaberating with Oak Ridge National Lab's research, GLCF will use a new precursor that can significantly reduce the cost of manufacturing carbon fiber through a fundamental change in processing. Precursor (raw material) represents 50% of the total cost of production for CF. The plan includes an initial production line within 24 months of the start date to produce 3.8 million pounds of fiber. The majority of this production is being sold prior to the production start date, primarily to wind blade manufacturers, composite product manufacturers and compounders. Initial planned annual sales are approximately $47M, increasing to $95M within four years of start with the addition of a second line. During this period EBITDA will range from $1.2M to $38M.
